  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Also known as \"scrofula\" when involves cervical lymph nodes\nMost common form of extrapulmonary\nTB\nTB causes up to 43% of peripheral lymphadenopathy in the developing world\n[1]\nIn the US, more common among Asian Pacific Islanders and in females\nMost cases occur in the setting of reactivation of latent infection",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "TB",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/TB"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Enlarging, painless, red, firm,\nmass\n, most commonly in the anterior or posterior cervical chain\nCan be complicated by ulceration, fistula, or\nabscess\nformation\nSystemic signs and symptoms are uncommon, except patients with\nHIV\n(in whom lymphadenitis is usually generalized)",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "mass",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Neck_mass"
        },
        {
          "text": "abscess",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Abscess"
        },
        {
          "text": "HIV",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/HIV"
        }
      ]
    },
